    <h1>Testimonial: Guitarist with Left Fretting Hand Dystonia</h1>
    <p>This case involved fretting-hand dystonia, where the ring and pinky fingers curled when placing the index and middle fingers on the guitar fretboard. This left-hand coordination loss is highly disruptive, particularly for complex chord transitions and speed playing.</p>
    
    <p>Through slow tactile-input retraining, we retaught the brain to distinguish independent finger pressure. The client gradually rebuilt left-hand agility, resolving the involuntary flexion and returning to a full practice schedule.</p>

    <blockquote>
      "The retraining process required patience, but isolating each finger's movement broke the pattern. My fretting hand is finally fluid and responsive again."
    </blockquote>
    
    <div style="margin-top: 2.5rem; display: flex; gap: 1rem;">
      <a href="/testimonials" class="btn btn-secondary">&larr; Back to Testimonials</a>
      <a href="/about/my-approach" class="btn">Read About Retraining</a>
    </div>
  </article>
